      becomes a node. attrs["string_type"] classifies as url/sql/path/
      registry/guid/base64/hex/format_str/error_msg/email/envvar/
      user_agent/generic. Edges: binary→string. URL strings auto-
      promote to HttpEndpoint via the existing source-code pipeline.
      Cap: 5000 strings per binary. ~6-byte minimum length.
    - Overlay (kind: "overlay") — data appended past the official
      end of a PE/ELF/Mach-O. Common malware/installer signal.
      Format-aware detection (PE: max(section.raw_end, cert_end);
      ELF: max(section_end, segment_end, sht_end)). Classified by
      signature: nsis_installer / inno_setup / pyinstaller / py2exe /
      self_extract (PK/7z) / authenticode_sig (benign — recognized
      and labeled rather than misflagged) / high_entropy_blob /
      generic. attrs["entropy"] / attrs["size"] / attrs["kind"].

  New module: src/strings.rs (~280 LOC) — StringType enum + classify().
  New module: src/actions/overlay.rs (~280 LOC) — detect_pe_overlay,
    detect_elf_overlay, shannon_entropy, OverlayKind classifier,
    overlay_info action.
  New helper: actions/reverse/common.rs::promote_strings_to_graph
    (FNV-1a-based stable string IDs, URL→endpoint chain).

  Wired into:
    - pe-strings → registers all extracted strings as StringLiteral
    - elf-info → extracts strings from full binary + promotes
    - pe-sections → auto-flags overlay + sets attrs["packed"] = "true"
      when any section's Shannon entropy > 7.0; attrs["max_section_
      entropy"] always set
    - new top-level action: `overlay-info <binary>` reports overlay
      with classification + size + entropy

  Live verification:
    - codemap binary (Rust ELF, 26 MB): 200+ StringLiteral nodes
      registered. meta-path "elf->string->endpoint" traces the
      embedded `file://` URL through string node to HttpEndpoint.
    - hand-crafted PE with PK\x03\x04 ZIP overlay: detected as
      "self_extract" at offset 0x1200, 1054 bytes, entropy 3.6.

  Tests: 146 passing (was 130). +16 new (12 string-classification,
  4 overlay/entropy).

  Action count: 146 → 148 (+2: overlay-info, lang-fingerprint
  already shipped in 5.12.0).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.12.2 — PE Rich header + TLS callbacks + entry-point analysis
  source: 5.13.0 task #38 lifted forward — these don't actually need
  the disasm framework (#36) so they shipped cleanly without it.

  New module: src/actions/pe_meta.rs (~340 LOC). Single new action:
  `pe-meta <pe-binary>` (alias `rich-header`).

  Features:
    - Rich header parsing — undocumented Microsoft fingerprint
      embedded between the DOS stub and PE signature. Records which
      cl.exe / link.exe / cvtres / masm versions produced each
      object file linked into the binary. Product-ID lookup table
      covers VS6 → VS2022. attrs["rich_msvc"] / attrs["rich_entries"]
      on the binary node.
    - TLS callbacks — TLS_DIRECTORY callback array. These run BEFORE
      main(), making them a common malware persistence vector.
      Detects + flags + lists callback RVAs. attrs["has_tls_callback"]
      / attrs["tls_callback_count"]. Surfaces ⚠ warning in output.
    - Entry-point analysis — AddressOfEntryPoint from optional
      header. attrs["entry_rva"] on binary node.

  All three live in one action so users don't need to remember
  three commands to triage a PE binary.

  Tests: 150 passing (was 146). +4 pe_meta tests.
  Action count: 148 → 149 (+1).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.13.0 — disasm framework + intra-binary call graph (#36 + #37)
  source: 5.13.0 task #36 (disasm framework) and #37 (call graph
  + xrefs) shipped together — once iced-x86 was integrated and
  function boundaries detected, the call edges were ~50 lines of
  additional code so they merged into one release.

  THE big disasm leap. Every graph algorithm in codemap (PageRank,
  Leiden, betweenness, Fiedler, spectral-cluster, eigengap heuristic,
  centrality measures, link prediction, temporal evolution) now
  works at the function-within-binary level — not just file-within-
  repo. PageRank can rank functions inside a stripped malware sample
  by call-graph importance. Fiedler can find natural bisection lines
  across a binary's internal functions.

  New EntityKind: BinaryFunction (kind: bin_func).

  New deps:
    - iced-x86 = "1" with default-features = false, features =
      ["std", "decoder", "masm"]. Pure Rust x86/x64 decoder, no
      system libs. ~2 MB compile impact.
    - capstone-rs intentionally NOT added — it links a C library,
      violates the single-binary-no-system-libs rule. ARM/MIPS
      support deferred until a pure-Rust solution is needed.

  New module: src/disasm.rs (~470 LOC) — format-agnostic disasm_binary
  entry point dispatches to disasm_pe / disasm_elf based on magic
  bytes. PE: walks export directory for symbols. ELF: walks
  .symtab/.dynsym for STT_FUNC entries. decode_functions runs iced-x86
  Decoder per function, terminates at RET / next-symbol-boundary.
  Tracks direct call targets (for intra-binary edges) and indirect
  call count separately.

  New module: src/actions/bin_disasm.rs (~150 LOC) — action wrapper.
  Registers BinaryFunction node per detected function with attrs:
  name (auto-demangled), address, size, instruction_count,
  indirect_calls, is_entry, mangled (raw, when demangled differs).
  Adds binary→bin_func edges + bin_func→bin_func edges for resolved
  intra-binary calls.

  v1 scope (intentional):
    - PE + ELF only (Mach-O deferred — same approach, just a
      different format reader)
    - x86/x64 only (machine = 3 / 0x3E for ELF, 0x14c / 0x8664 for
      PE; rejects ARM64 with clear error pointing at v1 limits)
    - Symbol-table-driven boundaries only (linear-sweep fallback
      on stripped binaries deferred)

  Live verification: codemap-on-itself x86_64 build (26 MB ELF,
  5.2 MB .text, not stripped) → 6187 functions detected from
  symtab. Top functions by size: ts_lex (118KB / 25K instrs —
  tree-sitter generated lexers), codemap_core::cpg::ensure_cpg
  (18KB / 3.4K instrs). Demangled Rust names + clap_builder
  C++-style namespaces all readable. PageRank over bin_func
  kind successfully ranks functions by intra-binary call-graph
  centrality. Disasm itself ~1s; default scan invariant unchanged
  (heavy operation behind explicit `bin-disasm` action).

  Tests: 150 passing (was 146 — no new unit tests for disasm yet
  since iced-x86 is the well-tested component; integration is
  validated by the live smoke run on a 6K-function binary).

  Action count: 149 → 150 (+1: bin-disasm with `disasm` alias).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.13.1 — WASM function-level disasm (#42)
  source: 5.14.0 task #42 lifted forward — WASM is a wonderfully
  structured format and the function-level extraction follows the
  same pattern as 5.13.0's iced-x86 work.

  Extends wasm-info to walk the Code section + register a
  BinaryFunction node per function (import or defined). Reuses the
  BinaryFunction EntityKind from 5.13.0 with attrs["binary_format"] =
  "wasm" so users can filter via meta-path / centrality / etc.

  Implementation: walk_wasm_code_for_graph (~200 LOC in binary.rs).
  Two-pass: first pass walks Import + Export sections to build the
  function-index → name table; second pass walks the Code section
  body-by-body, scanning instructions for `call` opcode (0x10) to
  emit intra-module call edges. `call_indirect` (0x11) bumps an
  indirect-call counter but doesn't add edges (the table-index
  resolution is more involved than v1 needs).

  Imports become bin_func nodes with kind_detail="import" and
  funcidx in [0..n_imports). Defined functions get
  kind_detail="defined" and funcidx in [n_imports..). Exported
  function names propagate to attrs["name"] when present, else
  "func_<funcidx>" placeholder.

  Live verification: hand-crafted 73-byte WASM with 1 import
  (env.print), 2 defined funcs (add, main where main calls both
  env.print + add) → meta-path "wasm->bin_func->bin_func" returns
  exactly the 2 expected paths.

  Pyc method-level (#41) deferred — Python's marshal format is
  recursive and needs a real walker to do robustly. Will land in
  a focused future session.

  Tests: 150 passing (no new unit tests; verification is the live
  smoke run).
  Action count: 150 (no new actions; wasm-info just got smarter).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.14.0 — supply-chain dimension (license-scan + cve-import + cve-match)
  source: 5.15.0 tasks #44 + #45 lifted forward — both add their own
  EntityKind, both fit cleanly in one release, and #45 (cve-match)
  proves the killer supply-chain meta-path that codemap now does
  natively where dedicated tools (Snyk, Trivy, Grype, syft) need a
  separate dependency-scanning pass.

  Two new EntityKinds:
    - License (kind: "license") — SPDX identifier nodes. attrs:
      spdx, family (permissive/weak_copyleft/strong_copyleft/
      proprietary/unknown), usage_count.
    - Cve (kind: "cve") — vulnerability records imported from
      offline NVD JSON dumps. attrs: id, severity (CRITICAL/HIGH/
      MEDIUM/LOW), cvss, year, cwe, description, cpe_products,
      cpe_full.

  Three new actions:
    - license-scan — walks the scan dir for SPDX-License-Identifier
      markers in source headers, license fields in 7 manifest
      formats (Cargo.toml, package.json, pyproject.toml, pom.xml,
      go.mod, gemspec, composer.json), and LICENSE/COPYING/NOTICE
      files matched against template fingerprints (15 known
      licenses: MIT, Apache-2.0, GPL family, LGPL family, AGPL,
      MPL-2.0, BSD-2/3, ISC, Unlicense, 0BSD, EPL-2.0, BSL-1.0,
      CC0-1.0). Registers source→license edges; the same License
      node is reused across all sources claiming it.
    - cve-import <nvd.json> — parses NVD JSON 1.1 or 2.0 schema
      (auto-detects from envelope shape). Registers a Cve node per
      record with full CPE 2.3 product extraction. No network —
      strictly offline.
    - cve-match — walks every Dll node in the graph, normalizes
      its name (strips `lib` prefix + .so/.dll/.dylib/.jar +
      version suffix), and matches against each Cve's CPE products.
      On match, adds a dll→cve edge. Together with the existing
      source→binary→dll edges, enables the killer query:
      meta-path "source->binary->dll->cve" finds vulnerable
      transitive dependencies in your code.

  False-positive fix: the SPDX-License-Identifier scanner was
  finding its own marker constant in license.rs source. Tightened
  the parser to require ≥2 alphabetic chars + a leading letter
  in the candidate, eliminating the recursive false-positive.

  Live verification:
    - codemap repo license-scan → 1 distinct SPDX (MIT, 2 hits in
      manifests).
    - Hand-crafted NVD JSON with one CVE-2099-99999 against
      `cpe:2.3:a:gnu:glibc` → cve-import registers the CVE,
      cve-match links it to libc.so.6 in codemap's ELF graph,
      meta-path "elf->dll->cve" returns the path
      `elf:/usr/local/bin/codemap → dll:libc.so.6 →
      cve:CVE-2099-99999` correctly.

  Tests: 163 passing (was 150). +13 unit tests (8 license, 5 cve).
  Action count: 150 → 153 (+3).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.14.1 — SBOM export (SPDX 2.3 + CycloneDX 1.5) (#47)
  source: 5.15.0 task #47 lifted forward — the prerequisites that
  matter (License nodes from #44, Cve nodes from #45) are already
  in 5.14.0. Code signing certs (#46) would enrich the SBOM further
  but aren't required for either standard's minimum viable doc.

  Two new actions, one new module (~360 LOC), zero new EntityKinds:
  pure read-side serialization of the heterogeneous graph.

    - to-spdx — emits SPDX 2.3 JSON. Linux Foundation standard,
      required for US federal procurement (Executive Order 14028).
      Source files / binaries / DLLs become SPDX packages with
      `primaryPackagePurpose` mapped from EntityKind. Licenses
      concluded via outgoing License-node edge or "NOASSERTION".
      Relationships: source DEPENDS_ON imp, dll DESCRIBES license,
      dll HAS_ASSOCIATED_VULNERABILITY cve.
    - to-cyclonedx — emits CycloneDX 1.5 JSON. OWASP standard,
      richer vulnerability section. Components include CPE refs
      pulled from cve-import metadata. Vulnerabilities are
      first-class with CVSS scores + descriptions + affected
      components. Dependencies section mirrors the heterogeneous
      graph's import edges.

  Graceful degradation: if no License or Cve nodes were registered,
  SPDX writes "NOASSERTION" (per the standard) and CycloneDX writes
  empty `vulnerabilities`. Skeletal SBOMs work; richer ones come
  from chaining license-scan + cve-import + cve-match first.

  Format compliance:
    - SPDX 2.3: required fields (spdxVersion, dataLicense, SPDXID,
      name, documentNamespace, creationInfo, packages,
      relationships) all populated.
    - CycloneDX 1.5: required fields (bomFormat, specVersion,
      serialNumber, version, metadata) all populated. Serial
      number is FNV-1a-derived UUID for determinism.

  Live verification: SBOM emitted on codemap repo (56 files) is
  valid JSON, parses cleanly via serde_json, contains all 56 source
  files as SPDXRef packages with relationships matching the
  scanner's import graph. Hand-fixture graph with License + Cve
  nodes round-trips correctly through both formats.

  Tests: 166 passing (was 163). +3 sbom unit tests covering JSON
  validity + required fields + ISO 8601 timestamp format.
  Action count: 153 → 155 (+2: to-spdx, to-cyclonedx).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.14.2 — fuzzy hashing (TLSH + ssdeep) (#48)
  source: 5.15.0 task #48 — fleet-level binary similarity. Pure
  Rust, no external dep. Both algorithm specs are stable and
  well-documented; our implementations are simple-but-correct.

  New module: src/actions/fuzzy.rs (~440 LOC). Two new actions,
  no new EntityKinds (similarity edges are added between existing
  binary nodes).

    - fuzzy-hash <binary> — computes TLSH (Trend Locality-Sensitive
      Hash, 2013) + ssdeep (Context-Triggered Piecewise Hash,
      2006). Stores both as attrs["tlsh"] / attrs["ssdeep"] on
      the binary node. Idempotent.
    - fuzzy-match [tlsh-threshold=70] — walks every binary node
      with a fuzzy hash, computes pairwise TLSH distance + ssdeep
      similarity. If TLSH ≤ threshold OR ssdeep ≥ 50, adds a
      similar_binary edge between the two binaries (symmetric).
      Then PageRank / Leiden / etc. treat similar binaries as
      connected — automatic clustering of variants.

  Algorithm correctness:
    - TLSH: 5-byte sliding window, 6 trigram permutations per
      window, Pearson hash buckets, quartile-based 2-bit nibble
      encoding. 70-char hex output starting with T1 prefix.
      Distance is bit-difference of header + 2-bit-pair body.
      Self-distance is 0; identical inputs produce identical
      hashes (verified).
    - ssdeep: Adler-style rolling hash for chunk boundaries,
      FNV-style trigger hash per chunk. Auto-adjusts blocksize
      to keep output ~64 chars. Format: BS:H1:H2. Similarity is
      Levenshtein-distance-based, normalized to 0-100. Self-
      similarity is 100 (verified).

  Tests: 173 passing (was 166). +7 fuzzy tests including
  identical-input identity, distance-grows-with-mutation,
  edit-distance correctness, ssdeep round-trip.

  Live verification: codemap binary on mater (26 MB ARM64 ELF)
  produces TLSH `T1BFC518470D8A...` + ssdeep
  `196608:Q0f9Niq1...` cleanly in <100ms.

  Action count: 155 → 157 (+2: fuzzy-hash, fuzzy-match).
